# Trivy vulnerability ignore list
#
# Format: <CVE-ID> [target:<artifact-path>] [exp:<YYYY-MM-DD>]
# Targeted ignores (Trivy >= 0.53.0) suppress a CVE only in the specified artifact path,
# leaving all other instances of the same CVE active.
# Reference: https://aquasecurity.github.io/trivy/latest/docs/configuration/filtering/#trivyignore-format
#
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# CVE-2026-33671 — picomatch ReDoS in npm's internal dependency tree
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# picomatch < 4.0.4 has a Regular Expression Denial of Service vulnerability
# in extglob pattern handling. The fix is picomatch >= 4.0.4.
#
# Our build tools in /usr/local/lib/node_modules/ are patched via package.json
# overrides (picomatch forced to 4.0.4 — see overrides in package.json and the
# "npm overrides" section in docs/pipeline-decisions.md).
#
# The remaining instance is in /usr/lib/node_modules/npm/ — npm's own internal
# dependency tree. This is the npm package manager installed by NodeSource, not
# any code we wrote or tools we invoke during the build. The ReDoS vector requires
# user-controlled input to reach picomatch's extglob parser; npm's internal use
# processes only trusted package manifest data during 'npm install'.
#
# Attempts to eliminate this via upgrading npm (10.x → 11.x) were made but npm@11.x
# bundles tinyglobby which also carries picomatch@4.0.3 — the CVE is in npm's own
# internal bundle regardless of version. This entry will be removed when NodeSource
# ships a Node.js version whose bundled npm no longer includes picomatch@4.0.3.
#
# Reference: https://avd.aquasec.com/nvd/cve-2026-33671
CVE-2026-33671 target:usr/lib/node_modules/npm/node_modules/picomatch/package.json
